@FullyTested
public final class UnmodifiableForwardingListIterator<TValue>
extends com.google.common.collect.ForwardingListIterator<TValue>

This class is a simple extension of ForwardingListIterator, where methods add(Object), remove(), and set(Object) are disabled -- always throw UnsupportedOperationException.

The class constructor is private. Instead, use static method of(ListIterator).

This class is final to disable modify-by-inheritance.

Why is this class not called ImmutableListIterator? Read more here: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/8892350/immutable-vs-unmodifiable-collection

Author:
Kevin Connor ARPE (kevinarpe@gmail.com)
See Also:
ForwardingListIterator, UnmodifiableForwardingIterator, of(ListIterator), UnmodifiableForwardingList.listIterator(), UnmodifiableForwardingList.listIterator(int)

of

public static <TValue> UnmodifiableForwardingListIterator<TValue> of(ListIterator<TValue> iter)
Returns an unmodifiable view of an underlying ListIterator. If the input is an instance of UnmodifiableForwardingListIterator, this method avoids wrapping the iterator again -- the input value is returned untouched.

Parameters:
iter - list iterator to create an unmodifable view
Returns:
an unmodifiable view of underlying list iterator
Throws:
NullPointerException - if iter is null
